The point is, cake was dinner. And then I came home and had nachoes for dessert. Pauline had a mexican themed birthday party last night, and there is so much food left over. Including a tray of refried beans layered with salsa. And bags and bags of carrot and celery sticks.

Why on earth did I refuse to eat refried beans for so long. They're great!

You know, when Pauline said her boy was coming over for dinner, I assumed she meant Washington. Who is this guy.?.?.?.?.?.?.?.?.?

Mayhem had our performance for family and friends last night.  It was totally awesome. I stuck all my tumbling and all my stunts. As a group, we lost a total of one lib, one 360 and one chair to hands in the chant part. When we finished I looked over at mum and her jaw was hanging off! 

Plus we had so much fun doing it!  

The really awesome thing is that 18 months ago I started back at gymnastics with the goal of being able to do a roundoff backflip.  I had the worst backflips ever. I would look over my shoulder and collapse on myself. And last night I did a roundoff backflip, on the floor, without mats, in between people, and in time with the music. I'd done them before, but it was like, hey. Stop. You can do it. You can do anything. 

Totally awesome feeling.

I might post some pictures later.

My mum went into hospital today to have a kidney biopsy. It really isn't a big deal. Unless you're my mother and you make it a big deal. And phone me twice at work and describe the view and then send me a message saying that its done and its fine and you're having lunch.

Actually, I haven't replied to that one..... I'm not really sure what to say. "Thats very nice" in the tone Liz uses comes to mind. The tone that means, congratulations, are you proud of yourself.

Its just, I'm very busy at the moment and I don't really care how many chairs are outside or how far away the carpark is and whether or not your nurse is outside smoking.....

sigh

Okay, so all the grief with the 360 groups is over. There are still two groups doing it, but the other two, including mine, aren't. Instead, I'm flying.  

I've been sick again this week with a stomach thing, so I haven't been at cheer and haven't had a chance to try the stunt, and so when I got to cheer tonight I asked beck if we're flying, and was very excited to hear that we were. And then we did it. 

Why did I agree to this..... Okay, the flying I can sort of deal with. It is just at prep level. But they're dropping me! I mean, not accidentally! I don't like being dropped. I don't really like being cradled, either. In fact, I prefer to fall out of stunts. Anyway, apparently the effect will be really good, but its fricking scary.  

I was up there and they're like, "okay, we're gonna drop, ready..." Um, no. I'm not. But I don't get a say in the matter!

She put me on anti-inflammatories, and told me no tumbling, no stunts, no dancing, no stretching, no combat kicks higher than my ankle, no leg workouts and, well, basically no fun, for at least a week.

You know, I've been thinking about comfort zones lately. The whole thing with pt is taking people out of their comfort zones. Most people's comfortable version of exercise isn't what they should be doing. And most people's version of comfortable eating isn't necessarily what they should be eating.  

The point is that you don't acheive anything new if you always do the same thing.

Now. Lets apply that theory to gymnastics, shall we? Mmm hmm?

The problem is that people are afraid of failing... And maybe not even failing to lift the weight or eat breakfast, but afraid that if they do everything right they still won't get the results and then they really will have failed...  

I guess the difference is that if I fail at backsaults, I could end up breaking my neck........

You know, I had a pretty good week at work this week. I mean, I cried a couple of times on Thursday.... But a few people I've written programs for in the past have had some really good results. One really big guy went to his doctor last week, and he's lost a few kilos, but his blood pressure is down. The doctor was really happy, and said that he sees a point where some people go where they can't turn back. And he'd been worried that this guy had already gone to that point. And now he's turned back. He told the doctor everything that he'd been doing (ie, everything I told him to do), and the doctor seemed very happy and encouraged him to keep at it! And one lady (who doesn't speak much english and put my patience to the test) only lost about 0.8 of a kilo, but when I took her measurements they were all pretty much the same except for one. Her waist. I had to redo it to check, cos she lost over 10 cm from it! And then my scared lady. One of the first programs I did. Ruben did her third last weekend, and I had a chat to her, and she's lost about 15 kilos, and dropped a dress size. Her family gave her lots of gift vouchers for her birthday so she can buy new clothes. She was petrified when she came in the first time, and now shes in there twice a day sometimes. Usually when her family refuses to go for a walk cos its too cold outside. They stay in front of the telly, and she comes and walks on a treadmill. And then the next morning shes out the front waiting for me at 5:50..... And one lady who was in a car accident and has no vision on the right side of either eye, and whose right arm is much weaker.... She had gone through like 4 or 5 programs... I gave her unilateral arm exercises, so she only works one side at a time, and tries not to do more on the good side than the weak side... Anyway, she came and told me she wants to stick with her current program for a bit longer, and its made such a difference. Her balance has improved so much that she was able to run on a treadmill without holding on for the first time since the accident! Which for some people might not seem like something to get excited about, but its had similar impacts on the rest of her life as well. Very cool. So anyway... Despite the tears, I had a good week...
